snippet.textDisplay: One of the better-written shows currently going, directors/writers Jonathan Nolan, Lisa Joy, and J.J. Abrams do not disappoint. Add equally talented and diverse cast to the mix and you're in for a treat. From the trailer it seems that the team pays close attention to the architecture when building the world and how it serves the story and its characters. Some cool locations are seen on this trailer, from Singapore to downtown LA, from Valencia to Besalú, and Barcelona where Ricardo Bofill's La Fábrica look brutalist and ultra-modern at the same time. Definitely a very different and more modern look from the first 2 seasons. Can't wait!

snippet.textDisplay: I hope I'm mistaken, but it seems to me that this season will be more of a generic action/dystopian future type of show, rather than the intriguing mystery show of the first and second season. What I enjoyed about Westworld for the entirety of Season 1 and the second half of Season 2 were its philosophical questions, clever and smoothly interconnected storylines, plot twists, and the suspense of never having the full picture/never quite knowing what was going on and what was going to happen. Those seasons' strengths were, in my opinion, their intelligence, and the best episodes were often not the ones with a lot of action and shooting - which is also why I didn't enjoy the first part of Season 2 as much as the rest. I remember thinking at the end of Season 2 that it would be difficult to maintain those qualities once the hosts entered the outside world, and the trailer seems to confirm that the show will move in a more action-heavy direction rather than continue on the philosophical track. But like I said, I hope I'm wrong, and if many of the same writers are involved, they might manage to make it work
snippet.textOriginal: I hope I'm mistaken, but it seems to me that this season will be more of a generic action/dystopian future type of show, rather than the intriguing mystery show of the first and second season. What I enjoyed about Westworld for the entirety of Season 1 and the second half of Season 2 were its philosophical questions, clever and smoothly interconnected storylines, plot twists, and the suspense of never having the full picture/never quite knowing what was going on and what was going to happen. Those seasons' strengths were, in my opinion, their intelligence, and the best episodes were often not the ones with a lot of action and shooting - which is also why I didn't enjoy the first part of Season 2 as much as the rest. I remember thinking at the end of Season 2 that it would be difficult to maintain those qualities once the hosts entered the outside world, and the trailer seems to confirm that the show will move in a more action-heavy direction rather than continue on the philosophical track. snippet.textDisplay: That Generic hero-esk almost light-hearted soundtrack they plastered on to these amazing visuals and narration really fell flat. The music was so off-putting to me personally that I almost didn't like the trailer lol. Somebody please tell the MD to dig deeper into a darker, edgier lo-fi, interesting pallet of sounds that feel like what this world is. Or go for a juxtaposition Fall out 4 throwback to evoke some kind of emotion for the next trailer for the love of God.

snippet.textDisplay: As much as I have enjoyed Maeve's journey, I do truly hope this is the final season. The Nolans were given far too much leash with this program, and HBO has hopefully decided to pull the plug & jerk the leash *hard*. Two years between seasons is inexcusable...especially since the seasons are so short. Only The Sopranos could get away with that. The creative team was massively overindulged, and while the visuals look stunning, the ratings will most likely be in the toilet because the audience to a large degree moved on to other things.
